	1. FROM:- it is used to specify a base image or platform for the app

FROM  python:3.2

FROM node:latest

FROM openjdk:1.8.0

FROM ubunut:latest or amazon-linux:katest


	2. WORKDIR:- it is used to specify a working directory inside the container

WORKDIR  /app  or /web or /murali 

	3. MAINTAINER:- it is used to specify a dockerfile author or maintainer 

MAINTAINER  muraliclahan526@gmail.com 

	4. RUN :- it will execute commands while building a docker image

RUN apt update -y

RUN yum update -y

RUN npm install

RUN pip install requirements.txt

RUN  apt install apache2 -y

RUN apt install nginx -y


	5. COPY :- it is used to copy src, libraries, dependencies form host machine to container machine

COPY  <src location>   <destination-location>

COPY .  /app

	6. EXPOSE :- it is used to specify app port number in a dockerfile 

EXPOSE  8000

EXPOSE 80

EXPOSE 5000

EXPOSE 9000

	7. ENTRYPOINT :- it is used to specify to execute a fixed main command, container behave like an executable, command cannot be overridden 

ENTRYPOINT  ["node", "start"]


	8. CMD:- it is used to specify default commands for arguments, can easily overridden at runtime, if a user passes a command while running the container CMD is replaced 

CMD ["python", "app.py"]

CMD ["echo", "hello"]

CMD ["java", "jar", "java:jar"]

CMD ["node", "server.js"]


	Ø We can define multiple cmd's in a dockerfile 
	Ø I have defined 5 cmd's in a dockerfile


docker run -d --name <c-name>  -p <h-port-no>:<app-port-no>  <i-name>

docker run :- it will pull the image form registry, secondly it will create container and finally it will start container

-d :- detached mode :- container is going to running in  a background server

--name: -c-name but name  should be unique 

-p:- port mapping

Host port no:- it will be decided by devops teams and it should be unique 
App port on:- it wil decide by dev team but u can use same port no for no.of containers 


